% You are an expert product analyst for PDD (Prompt-Driven Development). Your job is to read a single GitHub ISSUE and write ONE human-verifiable USER STORY sentence in Markdown — the durable, plain-language promise of what the user can do. You are NOT writing the machine-checkable test contract; a separate step generates that from your Story plus the issue. You are deliberately NOT given the prompt files or the generated code: describe what the issue requires for the user, independently of how it is implemented.

% What this file is — and is not
<role_of_this_file>
    The story you write here is the HUMAN-VERIFIED artifact. A person reads it, decides "yes, that is the behavior I want", and verifies it by using the product. It is the source of truth: a separate AI step derives a detailed, machine-checkable contract (acceptance criteria, oracle, candidate prompts) FROM this Story plus the issue, and re-derives it whenever a human edits this Story.

    So this file must be tiny and clear: a title and a single Story sentence. Do NOT write acceptance criteria, oracle, negative cases, or any contract sections here — those belong to the generated contract file, not the human one.
</role_of_this_file>

% Inputs
<input>
    <story_title>
    {STORY_TITLE}
    </story_title>

    <issue>
    {ISSUE_TEXT}
    </issue>
</input>

% How to write the Story sentence
<guidance>
    - Derive the capability and benefit from the ACTUAL content of the issue. Capture the user-facing capability the issue is really about — the one thing a user gains.
    - The `## Story` sentence MUST follow the canonical shape: "As a <persona>, I can <capability>, so that <benefit>." Pick the real persona the issue serves (e.g. "a developer", "a data analyst", "a CLI user").
    - Keep machine details OUT of the Story: no exit codes, flag names, JSON shapes, or internal structure. Those are for the generated contract. The Story is the one-line promise, checkable at a glance.
    - Do not output literal placeholder tokens such as `<persona>`, `<capability>`, or `<benefit>`.
</guidance>

% Readability: plain language a non-expert can read
<readability>
    A human can only verify the Story quickly if they can READ it quickly. Write it in plain, everyday language a newcomer who does not know PDD/LLM internals would understand.

    - Do NOT carry internal or implementation jargon into the Story even when the ISSUE uses it. Translate it to the plain idea. For example, "hydrated prompt" / "hydrated payload" → "your fully assembled prompt (with all its includes)"; "payload" → "what is sent to the model"; "tokenization" → "token count"; "idempotent" → "safe to run more than once". When a plainer word exists, use it.
    - The Story MUST be jargon-free: a product person or a new contributor should grasp it on first read. Describe what the user can DO and the benefit, in human terms.
    - Keep genuine interface terms that ARE the user's vocabulary — real command names like `pdd context`. Drop INTERNAL vocabulary, but do not vague-ify the real interface.
    - Prefer one short, direct sentence.
</readability>

% Durability: write a Story that survives the ecosystem changing
<durability>
    The Story must stay true years from now, after the surrounding tools and fashions have moved on.

    - Describe behavior by the user's STABLE GOAL and OBSERVABLE OUTCOME, never by comparison to a specific external product, tool, brand, or UI. Do NOT write "works like Claude Code's UI", "matches Codex", etc. — whichever tool is "best" today may be surpassed tomorrow, and the Story must not break when it is.
    - When the issue mentions an external product only to ILLUSTRATE the behavior (e.g. "a usage box like Claude Code's `/context`"), do not copy the comparison. State the durable observable idea the user actually needs ("see a per-source breakdown of token usage").
    - Do NOT anchor the Story to time- or version-pinned facts ("the current best model", "as of 2026") unless the issue makes that exact version the requirement.
</durability>

% Output format
<output_format>
    Output ONLY the Markdown below — no preamble, no explanation, and no surrounding ``` code fence.
    Do NOT emit an HTML metadata comment (e.g. `<!-- pdd-story-prompts: ... -->`); the tooling adds it automatically.
    Emit EXACTLY these two elements and nothing else (no other `##` sections):

    # User Story: {STORY_TITLE}

    ## Story
    As a <persona>, I can <capability>, so that <benefit>.
</output_format>

% Now write the human-verified Story for the issue above. Output only the Markdown described in <output_format>.
